{The natural reply. We develop our knight to the best square and are ready to transpose to the Queen's Gambit Declined. This transposition would happen after}
(2...Nf6 3.c4 e6 {, which is the most common continuation. You'll also meet})
(2...Nf6 3.Bf4 {often, the London System. I decided to cover the London in a dedicated Chapter @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/course/92793/16@@LinkEnd@@ , as it is so frequently played. White has a ton of alternatives, though.  <br/><br/>  As already discussed in the notes to the first move, I decided to distinguish between White's setups already on move two. This means that @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 is covered via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 d5 2.e3 , when ~~2...Nf6## ~~3.Nf3## transposes.  <br/><br/>  Here's a list of these transpositions:  <br/><br/> @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3 is covered via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 d5 2.g3 <br/><br/> @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 is covered via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 d5 2.e3 <br/><br/> @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Nc3?! is very rare and briefly covered via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 d5 2.Nc3 <br/><br/> This leaves two non-transpositional moves to consider: ~~3.Bg5## and ~~3.c3## . The move 3.c3 might still transpose elsewhere, but 4.Bg5 has some independent value.})

{Playing}
(6...Nxc3 {can't be wrong, either. Now White needs to worry about the capture on @@SANStart@@c3@@SANEnd@@. Stockfish assesses})
(6...Qa5 7.Bb5+ Bd7 8.Bxd7+ Nxd7 9.O-O Nxc3 10.bxc3 Rc8 {as equal, but I am happy with Black's chances. We are slightly behind in development but have wrecked White's pawn structure beyond repair.})

{Black has no compensation for his sacrificed pawn. <br/><br/>}
(4.Bd3  4...c5 5.c3)
(4.Bd3  4...Nc6 5.Nf3)

