{Black tries to justify the Bb4 move.  <br/><br/>}
(10...Qa5 11.Ne4 {does not solve the problem of Black's passive bishop on c8 and gives White an option to gain tempos with a3-b4. After})
(10...Qh5 11.h3 {the queen won't be safe for a long time there when White plans Be2-Ne5.})

{Black needs some safety on c7. After}
(6...Bxb2? 7.Rb1 Bd4 8.Bb4! Bxf2+ 9.Ke2 {Black is falling apart. A slow move like})
(6...Nf6? {is refuted by} 7.Bb4 Qc6 8.Bb5! {, which illustrates the fork problem on c7.})

{We are aiming for the Scotch Four Knights Opening. This line enjoys a very good reputation as it features quick development for White and a very sound pawn structure. It is easier to learn and understand than the main alternatives, the Italian (Giuoco Piano) and Spanish (Ruy Lopez) Opening.}
({The Scotch Four Knights may also arise after the immediate} 3.d4 {, after which Black's most popular continuation is indeed} 3...exd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 {, which transposes to our repertoire.}
({Once you have mastered the Scotch Four Knights via our 3Nc3 move order, it makes a lot of sense to add the Scotch move order with} 3.d4 {to your repertoire. This way you get similar structures but some additional options like} 3...exd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nxc6 {.})
({Of course Black also has some extra choices, most notably} 4...Bc5 {, or my favourite}) (4...Bb4+ {. <br/><br/>Our line, the Scotch Four Knights, is easier to learn as it cuts down options for both sides.} ))

{8...Qe7 is the best engine move here but is third most popular. Sielecki doesn't cover this annoying pawn push but it's the most popular pleb move and second best engine move.}
(8...Bxc3+ 9.Qxc3)
(8...Qe7 9.O-O-O Bxc3 10.Qxc3 Qxe4 11.Bd3 {is suicidal for Black, says Christof.})

{Qc4 and Qd3 also work, and score better in the small sample of lichess pleb games.}
({Now if} 9.Qe5+  9...Qe7 {, engine likes} 10.Qxc7 {best, although} 10...Nxe4 11.O-O-O Nxc3 12.bxc3 Ba3+ 13.Kd2 {seems dicey? But engine says White is better.})
(9.Qe5+  9...Qe7 10.Qxe7 Kxe7 11.Bd2 {is also okay for White.})

{is the recent trend to pin the f6-knight immediately. The plus point is that the White queen can now go to either Qe2 or Qf3 to pressurize the f6-knight followed by long castle. So White by this move order has many flexible plans and rich ideas. Before}
(7.Qe2 {was heavily played, but Black found some nice ideas here with} 7...a5! {creating counterplay and preparing ...a4. If}
(7...O-O?! {is not so accurate due to} 8.Bg5 {and if} 8...a5 {now White can hop on with} 9.Nd5 {That's the major difference of first playing ...a5 and later doing it}) 8.a4 O-O {White has now made a weakness with the a4-pawn push, so Black will be able to neutralize the} 9.Bg5 {pin after} 9...Nb4 10.O-O-O d5 {with complex play. One more key note is if})
(7.Qe2 a5 8.a4 O-O 9.Be3 {here is not effective as Black is in time to achieve the} 9...d5 {break immediately.} 10.Bxb6 cxb6 11.O-O-O Re8 12.Qe3 Bd7 {and Black is fine.})

{In case Black immediately takes on d4 @@StartBracket@@without first playing ... Nc6@@EndBracket@@ , White should recapture with the Queen. The reason is that after the queen exchange, the endgame is quite unpleasant for Black. The alternative}
(7.Nxd4 {is well met by} 7...Bc5 {!} 8.Nb3 {Trying to avoid the queen exchange with}
(8.c3 {is met by} 8...e5)
(8.Be3 {is also no good in view of} 8...Qb6) 8...Qxd1 {= Black exchanged queens under much more favorable circumstances compared to 7. Qxd4. White will need to lose a tempo with Bxd1 and the knight on b3 is not as active as on d4.})

{is the recent trend to pin the f6-knight immediately. The plus point is that the White queen can now go to either Qe2 or Qf3 to pressurize the f6-knight followed by long castle. So White by this move order has many flexible plans and rich ideas. Before}
(7.Qe2 {was heavily played, but Black found some nice ideas here with} 7...a5! {creating counterplay and preparing ...a4. If}
(7...O-O?! {is not so accurate due to} 8.Bg5 {and if} 8...a5 {now White can hop on with} 9.Nd5 {That's the major difference of first playing ...a5 and later doing it}) 8.a4 O-O {White has now made a weakness with the a4-pawn push, so Black will be able to neutralize the} 9.Bg5 {pin after} 9...Nb4 10.O-O-O d5 {with complex play. One more key note is if})
(7.Qe2 a5 8.a4 O-O 9.Be3 {here is not effective as Black is in time to achieve the} 9...d5 {break immediately.} 10.Bxb6 cxb6 11.O-O-O Re8 12.Qe3 Bd7 {and Black is fine.})

{This isn't a good move, but seems like an annoying thing White would do, and sometimes does in pleb games. Engine says best and really only move is for White to castle, and that's what happens most often.}
(7.O-O Nxe4! 8.Re1 Nf6)
(7.Nxd4 {is also played sometimes, and then it's kind of a toss-up. Masters have played 7...Nxd5 in the few games in db, with drawish results. Engine likes three different moves about the same, giving a slight edge to Black, and with about 50/50 results} 7...Nxd4 {or}) (7...Nxe4 {or}) (7...Ne5 {and}) (7...Nxd5 {is fine enough as well. You'll have to play a chess game at this point.})

{By far the main move.}
(5.d3 {is legal, but it gains in strength against our repertoire a move later. Don't expect to face it very often, either - 5. d3 is usually done to force Open Spanish experts - <br/><br/>}) (5.O-O Nxe4 {- out of their comfort zone.})
(5.d3 b5 6.Bb3 Bc5 {makes a lot of sense now that the pawn can no longer go to d4 in one go, hitting the bishop on c5.})

{They'll probably still try this, since sacrificing on f7 is a core part of their personality. <br/><br/> Best would be to retreat to Nf3, having wasted tempi, when we should then play Nf6.}
(5.f4 d5!)
(5.h4 Nf6 6.Bc4 O-O 7.c3 Bc5)

{I like this move. Mainly because it works, but also because you will start hating that c6-knight as a 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 player after a while. Often it is dominated by a pawn on c3, controlling the d4 and b4 squares. Often it blocks the view of our bishop that would be eager to get a clear sight on b7. Often it has to go to the rim on a5 or back to b8, just to clear the way for the c-pawn. Often we need to spend two tempi on Ne7-Ng6 or Nd8-Ne6 to get it to a decent square. Long story short: it feels good to exchange that knight early on. In the Marshall that right costs us a pawn, here it's free ! OK, after 9. Bxf7 it might cost a pawn too. Still, we're happy !}
(8...d6 9.c3 {This transposes back. Not the end of the world, but the position after} 9...Bg4 10.Be3 {in particular, never struck me as an easy one for Black.})
(8...exd4 {This is not the best of ideas.} 9.e5 Ne8 10.Bd5!? {The knight on} 10...c6 {is just standing in the way. That's why we trade it off first.})

{My choice. It is currently less sexy than Nf6 and sacrificing two pieces later @@StartBracket@@see line above@@EndBracket@@ . I still like it better, it appeals to common sense and also puts direct pressure on the white center. The point is of course that White can not take on d5 and follow it up with Nc3 chasing our queen around, as putting the pawn on c3 has made that option illegal.}
(3...Nf6 {This is the trendy move. I will explain why and why I decided not to give it in a second, but it is perfectly fine too.} 4.d4 Nxe4 5.d5 {so far well known.} 5...Bc5! {This is a fun line that I first read about in Ntirlis'} 5.e4 {e5 book. It holds, but it leads to insane complications where Black often starts two pieces down. My reasoning not to make this our mainline is that this is probably the one line white Ponziani players will be ready for and if they are, it could be a bit tricky to navigate all that insanity over the board/from our memory. Therefore I went with 3... d5 @@StartBracket@@, but if you feel like exploring this instead, do your thing ! As far as I know, things end peacefully with best play.@@EndBracket@@}
(5.Ne7 Nxe5 6.Ng6 Nxg6 7.hxg6 Bd3 {is a bit better for White.}) 6...dxc6 6.Bxf2+ Ke2 7.Bb6 Qd5 8.Nf2 Rg1 9.O-O cxb7 10.Bxb7 Qxb7 11.Qf6 Qd5 12.c6 Qd2 13.e4 Nd4 14.e3 Qc2 {is a sample for how these lines go.} 15.Rae8 Qf5 16.Qd6 Na3 17.Bxd4 Nc4 18.Qxh2 cxd4 19.Ne4 Kd3 20.Nf2+ Ke2 21.Ne4 Kd3 22.Nf2+ {Are you not entertained ?})

{It's possible to hang on to the pawn with}
(7...Na5 {, but})
(7...e5! {is a lot stronger.})

{Here}
(8.Na3 {might be better, but} 8...Bxa3 {, followed by ...Be6 secures the extra pawn. There are tempting alternatives, like})
(8.e4 {, but we are spoilt for choice.})

{After}
(9.Qh4 {, White's queen is quickly running out of squares. The moves} 9...h6 {, or}) (9...Be7 {are strong and get us close to winning already.})
(9.Qc3 Bb4)
